This needs to work:

{code}
struct OidWrapper: Decodable {
  let id: ObjectId
}

let testDoc: Document = [
  "id": ObjectId(fromString: "57e193d7a9cc81b4027498b5")
]

print(try BsonDecoder().decode(OidWrapper.self, from: testDoc))
{code}

Following Github installation instructions, get the following error after modifying Package.swift as per instructions.

{code}
error: the package PackageReference(identity: "mongo-swift-driver", name: nil, path: "https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-swift-driver.git", isLocal: false) @ 0.0.2 contains revisioned dependencies:
PackageReference(identity: "swift-bson", name: nil, path: "https://github.com/mongodb/swift-bson", isLocal: false) @ master
PackageReference(identity: "swift-mongoc", name: nil, path: "https://github.com/mongodb/swift-mongoc", isLocal: false) @ master
{code}

Pointed out by [~jmikola], we should validate the provided data to make sure it matches up with what a UUID should be like: 
{quote}Some third-party tooling depends on that even though the server does not care. IMO an exception is helpful to warn users about misusing these sub-types. For instance, some were storing the string representation of a UUID (hexadecimals and dashes) instead of an actual binary value with the UUID sub-type, which is technically incorrect.
{quote}

Even if we do {{extension BsonValue: Equatable \{...}}} (-which we may as well, because all of our BSON types will always be {{Equatable}} too-) we can't actually make arbitrary {{BsonValues}} comparable via {{==}} because of restrictions preventing protocols from conforming to themselves, {{==}} only can only be applied to two instances of a concrete type conforming to {{Equatable}}, and not just instances of possibly different types that are both {{Equatable.}}

However, we _can_ provide a convenience method that takes in two arbitrary {{BsonValue}}s and compares whether they are equal. To implement that we can do something like
{code:java}switch left, right {
case let l as Int, let r as Int: return l == r
case let l as Double, let r as Double: return l == r
// ... all the other bson types
}
{code}
 

We could additionally write a custom Nimble matcher that uses this, so we could do something like {{expect(doc["a"]).to(bsonEqual(doc["b"])).}}

The compiler complains as follows:

{code:java}
/Users/kaitlinmahar/mongo-swift-driver/Sources/MongoSwift/BSON/Document+Sequence.swift:42:17: warning: instance method 'filter' nearly matches defaulted requirement 'filter' of protocol 'Sequence'
    public func filter(_ isIncluded: (KeyValuePair) throws -> Bool) rethrows -> Document {
                ^
/Users/kaitlinmahar/mongo-swift-driver/Sources/MongoSwift/BSON/Document+Sequence.swift:42:17: note: candidate has non-matching type '((Document.KeyValuePair) throws -> Bool) throws -> Document' (aka '(((key: String, value: Optional<BSONValue>)) throws -> Bool) throws -> Document') [with Element = Document.KeyValuePair, Iterator = DocumentIterator, SubSequence = Document]
    public func filter(_ isIncluded: (KeyValuePair) throws -> Bool) rethrows -> Document {
                ^
/Users/kaitlinmahar/mongo-swift-driver/Sources/MongoSwift/BSON/Document+Sequence.swift:42:17: note: move 'filter' to another extension to silence this warning
    public func filter(_ isIncluded: (KeyValuePair) throws -> Bool) rethrows -> Document {
                ^
Swift.Sequence:8:17: note: requirement 'filter' declared here
    public func filter(_ isIncluded: (Self.Element) throws -> Bool) rethrows -> [Self.Element]
                ^
{code}

I had placed this method inside Sequence because I mistakenly thought it was overriding the default implementation of filter Sequence provides. However, it appears that is not the case, and that the user actually still has access to the other impl if they explicitly request a return type of [Document.Element]. The one we provide is simply the default when an array is not requested:

{code:swift}
        let doc: Document = ["x": 1, "y": 2]

        let arr: [Document.Element] = doc.filter { $0.key != "x" }
        print(arr) // prints [(key: "y", value: Optional(2))]

        let doc2 = doc.filter { $0.key != "x" }
        print(doc2) // prints { "y" : 2 }
{code}


We can easily fix this warning by just placing the filter method in an extension of its own. 

We should also add a test verifying the behavior of our filter vs the default filter.

{{Document.merge}} was added for internal use in {{MongoCollection.createIndexes}}, but was marked {{public}}.

Its behavior is not consistent with other public API methods for modifying documents, in that it doesn't verify that a key doesn't already exist in the document before adding it. This makes it very fast and fine for internal usage whn we know duplicates aren't a problem, but it's not very safe for users.

Users can already safely accomplish this in this public API by doing something like:
{code:java}
var doc1 = Document()
let doc2: Document = ["a": 1, "b": 2]
doc2.forEach { doc1[$0.key] = $0.value } {code}
Therefore, there is no need to expose this and we should make it {{internal}} rather than {{public}}.

Additionally, it appears that the only time {{bson_concat}} returns false is if the merged documents would be over the max allowed size for a {{bson_t}}. We shouldn't rely on that always being the only reason for a false return value, but we can mention in the error message that the issue is *probably* related to document size.

As mentioned by [~kaitlin.mahar] in the [PR|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-swift-driver/pull/130] for SWIFT-226, we should, once that PR is merged, use the newly added Nimble matcher for {{bsonEqual}} to replace code like:

{code}
expect(doc["a"] as? Int).to(equal(5))
{code}
to
{code}
expect(doc["a"]).to(bsonEqual(5))
{code}

As proposed by [~matt.broadstone]:

Similarly to [JSONDecoder's dateDecodingStrategy|https://developer.apple.com/documentation/foundation/jsondecoder/2895216-datedecodingstrategy], we should allow a user to choose how both Dates and UUIDs gets decoded.

The Date strategy should be pretty much identical to the {{JSONDecoder}} behavior there, though we may want to default to our current date decoding strategy instead of deferring to Date like JSONDecoder does by default.

We should provide an analogous option for UUIDs, so that we can support decoding them in the reverse manner of how [this PR|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-swift-driver/pull/162] encodes them in {{UUID.encode(to storage....)}}. 

[We already special case|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-swift-driver/blob/master/Sources/MongoSwift/BSON/BSONDecoder.swift#L210-L212] ambiguous errors involving Date decoding, and we should do the same for UUID too.

These options should be added via {{open}} properties on {{BSONDecoder}} that users can set, i.e. with something like:
{code:java}
let decoder = BSONDecoder()
decoder.dateDecodingStrategy = .deferredToDate {code}
Therefore this will require implementing SWIFT-260.

We sneakily add {{_id}} fields to documents if they are missing them in {{insertOne}} and {{insertMany}}, even though the documents are not passed in as inout parameters. We should not do that.

This line is the culprit:
{code:java}
try ObjectId().encode(to: document.storage, forKey: "_id"){code}

This causes the document's {{count}} property to be out of date, leading to precondition failures.

Right now, we throw an error returned from {{bsonDecodingDirectly}} when encountering a {{_BSONEncoder}} in the decoder initializers for driver introduced BSON types. We do this so that e.g. {{decoder.decode(ObjectId.self, from: doc)}} will throw a nice error, but we're throwing the same error in the following case:
{code:java}
struct A: Codable {
    let a: ObjectId
}
try BSONDecoder().decode(A.self, from: ["a": "asdfasdf"]) // will call through to ObjectId.init
{code}
which doesn't make sense. We should update this to throw a better error message in the latter case.

{{bsonEquals}} is long and full of duplicated code. It's also prone to bugs if we forget to update it when we conform a new type to {{BSONValue}}. We should amend the {{BSONValue}} protocol to include the {{bsonEquals}} functionality, and add extension like this:
{code:java}
extension BSONValue where Self: Equatable { 
    func bsonEquals(other: BSONValue) { 
        guard let otherAsEquatable = other as? Self else { return false } 
        return self == otherAsEquatable 
    } 
}
{code}
For all {{BSONValues}} that conform to {{Equatable}}, the {{bsonEquals}} defined here will work automagically. This should include every {{BSONValue}} except for {{Array}}, which will require some additional massaging. It will give us a compiler error if we introduce a {{BSONValue}} type that doesn't conform to {{Equatable}} or implement this function, which is nice.

With this design, we'll be able to do {{a.bsonEquals(b)}} and remove the standalone {{bsonEquals}} function we have now, or replace the large body with simply {{lhs.bsonEquals(rhs)}}.

-This all requires conditional conformance, so it will have to come after we officially drop Swift 4.1.-

Creating new indexes with _expireAfter_ throws an error:

*+Example code:+*

 
{code:java}

{code}
*// Configure Mongo
let client = try MongoClient(Constants.mongo.url)
services.register(client)


let model = IndexModel(keys: ["createdAt": 1], options: IndexOptions(expireAfter: 10))
try client.db("auth").collection("keys").createIndex(model)*

 

 

+*Error:*+

 
{code:java}

{code}
*Fatal error: Error raised at top level: MongoSwift.ServerError.commandError(code: 197, message: "The field \'expireAfter\' is not valid for an index specification. Specification: \{ key: { createdAt: 1 }, name: \"createdAt_1\", expireAfter: 10 }", errorLabels: nil): file /BuildRoot/Library/Caches/com.apple.xbs/Sources/swiftlang/swiftlang-1001.8.63.13/swift/stdlib/public/core/ErrorType.swift, line 200***

 

The problem is that Mongo expects a parameter name _expireAfterSeconds_ and MongoSwift uses _expireAfter_.

+There are a simple solutions applying to *IndexModel* struct+
 # Change _expireAfter_ key to _expireAfterSeconds_
 # Add coding key string like _expireAfter = "expireAfterSeconds"_

When we skip a test based on server version we print something of the form:

{code:java}
Skipping test case A successful find event with a getmore and killcursors for server version ServerVersion(major: 4, minor: 2, patch: 0)
{code}

We should make {{ServerVersion}} conform to {{CustomStringConvertible}} so that we could just print "4.2.0" there instead.

A read concern of nil can mean different things, depending on the context.

If a client/db/collection's readConcern property is nil, that means it does not have a read concern set on it / it is using the server default read concern.

However, imagine a user does the following:

{code:java}
let client = try MongoClient(options: ClientOptions(readConcern: ReadConcern(.local)))
let db = client.db("foo", options: DatabaseOptions(readConcern: nil))
{code}

In this case, you might imagine that the {{nil}} read concern provided for the DB would override the local read concern that the db will by default inherit from the client.

However, that is not the case. Doing {{DatabaseOptions(readConcern: nil)}} is equivalent to doing {{DatabaseOptions()}}. So the db will end up with the local read concern inherited from the client.

One proposed solution is to implement an enum that is like an optional but has three states: some, none, and default.

Alternatively we stop using nil to mean default/unset read concern, and just use an empty read concern ReadConcern(). 

All this applies to WriteConcern as well.

All of our spec test files copy paste lines that look like:


{code:java}
let specsPath = MongoSwiftTestCase.specsPath + "/initial-dns-seedlist-discovery/tests"
let testFiles = try FileManager.default.contentsOfDirectory(atPath: specsPath).filter { $0.hasSuffix(".json") }
for filename in testFiles {
    let testFilePath = URL(fileURLWithPath: "\(specsPath)/\(filename)")
    let testDocument = try Document(fromJSONFile: testFilePath)
    ....
}
{code}

We should add a helper that takes in the folder name e.g. "initial-dns-seedlist-discovery" and returns a {{[(filename, Document)]}}.

An array should only be a BsonValue if all of its elements are BsonValue?s. Now that Swift 4.2 completes conditional conformance, we can provide better type safety around what arrays can be added to documents. 

We [currently|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-swift-driver/blob/b5f7e5783da71270fa80f5bad7c28159dab3e1e6/Sources/MongoSwift/BSON/BsonValue.swift#L106] just silently fail and convert anything that couldn't be cast to a BsonValue to nil.

For example:

 
{code:java}
let arr: [Int16] = [1, 2, 3, 4]
 var doc = Document()
 doc["a"] = arr
print(doc) // { "a" : [ null, null, null, null ] }
{code}
 
*NOTE*: [~kaitlin.mahar] brought up a [good point|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-swift-driver/pull/136#discussion_r230835599] about how we may want to instead support arrays of {{Codable}} ({{[Codable]}}).

Currently the async client's {{close}} method returns a future that resolves when it is done destroying its underlying libmongoc client pool and shutting down its {{NIOThreadPool}}.

However, in many basic use cases, e.g. a Vapor application, we expect a user to use a single {{MongoClient}} for the lifetime of their application, only shutting it down when their application is shutting down.

In those situations, the user is likely going to close the client in a {{defer}} block that executes just before the application stops.

The code for that looks something like
{code:java}var env = try Environment.detect()
try LoggingSystem.bootstrap(from: &env)
let app = Application(env)
defer {
    try! app.mongoClient.close().wait()
    app.shutdown()
}
try configure(app)
try app.run()
{code}
Rather than making the user {{wait}} on the returned future (which they have to {{try!}} / {{try?}} , even though it will never fail), we could introduce a {{syncClose}} method which synchronously closes the libmongoc client pool and shuts down the thread pool.

Vapor's {{Application.shutdown}} is already blocking as it calls {{self.eventLoopGroup.syncShutdownGracefully()}}. 

This would be in line with the APIs for {{EventLoopGroup}} and {{NIOThreadPool}}, which both provide (async) {{shutdown}} and {{syncShutDownGracefully}} methods.

As described in CDRIVER-2829, we cannot use {{bson_copy_to_excluding}} in its current form because we can't call variadic C functions from Swift.

CDRIVER-2829 will allow us to use a {{va_list}} (which we can create from Swift) to supply the variable-length list of fields to exclude. 

We will be able to use this in three places to optimize performance when we remove elements from documents, noted by TODOS:
 * {{DocumentIterator.subsequence}}
 * {{Document.setValue}}
 * {{Document.subscript}}

doing this will require dropping libmongoc < 1.14.

Running the following code in Swift 5.2 release mode triggers a segfault:
{code:java}
let doc: Document = ["a": [1]]
{code}
The issue occurs when we call {{bson_append_array}}. It seems that on the border of Swift and C the data in the temporary document representing the array gets garbled. This may be related to inlining.

Debugging via lldb and Xcode has not yielded any answers, so we should create a minimal example and post on the forums to see if anyone who works on the Swift compiler knows what the issue might be.

We prefix a number of our top level types with "Mongo" to disambiguate them and aid in discoverability (e.g. {{MongoCollection}}). Some of our types lack this prefix, and we should consider adding them.

Types that need consideration:
 - {{ClientSession}}
 - {{ClientOptions}}
 - {{ChangeStream}}
 - {{DatabaseOptions}}
 - {{CollectionOptions}}

We should also prefix our BSON types with {{BSON}} as many of them have potential to clash with names from other libraries. This could lead to breaking the compilation of our users' code when they pull in minor version updates from other libraries they use or make a minor version Swift update as suddenly they would need to prefix all conflicting types with {{MongoSwift}}.

Most of these types are in the {{BSON}} library. Let's prefix all of the core BSON types there with {{BSON}}. 

Non-BSON types we should also probably prefix:
 * Hint
 * Address
 * WriteModel? maybe should be BulkWriteModel?

If a non-decoding error is encountered on the last result of a cursor iteration, any for loop iterating over it will continue endlessly with all the results being LogicError's indicating that advancing a failed cursor is an error. We should ensure that nil has been returned at least once before returning such an error to ensure this doesnt happen.

repro with a collection with 2 documents in it:
{code}        
let client = try MongoClient.makeTestClient()
let cursor = try client.db("woo").collection("woo").find([:], options: FindOptions(batchSize: 1))
let fp = FailPoint.failCommand(failCommands: ["getMore"], mode: .alwaysOn, errorCode: 10)
try fp.enable()
for result in cursor {
    print(result)
}
// .document()
// .failure(errorCode 10)
// .failure(LogicError)
// .failure(LogicError)
// ..

{code}

In {{findOne}}, we ensure we only kill the cursor after a successful document retrieval since we assume the cursor will clean itself up appropriately after encountering an error. Cursors do not close themselves after encountering \{{DecodingError}} s, however, and in those cases we leak the cursor.
{code}struct Blah: Decodable {
    let lfkjadsjkla: String
}
let coll = db.collection("blah", withType: Blah.self)
try coll.findOne([:]).wait()
{code}
yields (in Debug mode)
{code}Assertion failed: cursor or change stream wasn't closed before it went out of scope: file /home/patrick/mongo-swift-driver/Sources/MongoSwift/CursorCommon.swift, line 247
{code}

{{equalsIgnoreKeyOrder}}, which compares two documents for equality without considering order of the keys, currently ensures documents contained in arrays have the same key order, while not ensuring regular subdocuments have the same key order. This should be fixed so that documents contained in arrays are compared without considering key order too.
{code:java}
// this should be true but is currently false
["x": [["a": 1, "b": 2]]].equalsIgnoreKeyOrder(["x": [["b": 2, "a": 1]]]){code}

